msDesc.head: Sermons on the saints, Conradus de Saxonia

p.note: and are the orignal pastedowns, which have been moved to the current position when the binding was renovated.

collation.p: The manuscript is too fragile to collate. It seems to consist mainly of quinternions.

msItem.title: Sermons
msItem.incipit: Vade in pace et cetera lucas x vii (Luke 7:50) hodie celebramus festum peccatorum
msItem.explicit: vii pertinentes ad diuinitatem et vii ad humanitatem et cetera

note.p: After the last line on the words quere retro tali signo and a sign (there is also a reference to the folio in question by a later hand) points the reader to the continuation of the text on .

msItem.title: Sermons on the saints
msItem.rubric: Incipiunt sermones fratris chunradi de saxonia de sanctis andree apostoli
msItem.incipit: Extendam palmas meas ad dominum Exodus ix (Exo 9:29) hoc uerbum Moysi beatus andreas apostolus potuit dicere
msItem.explicit: glorie digni sunt qui bene presunt vobis ergo bene preesse concedat qui cum patre in uni et cetera Amen
msItem.note: Agrees to a large part with the Paris 1521 print (Pseudo-)Bonaventure, Sermones de sanctis de quibus et eorum, although not always in the same order. Begins with St Andrew and ends with Sermo ad prelatos (corresponds to De Rectoribus Ser. II Fo. CLXXIX in the printed version).

supportDesc.condition: Parchment worn and damaged throughout. Holes from bookworms at the beginning and end. : hole through the leaves, perhaps caused by fire. Signs of contemporary repairs in places, e.g. . Text damaged by damp in several places, e.g . : upper inner corner missing with loss of 2-3 words of text.

layout.note: Guidelines and ruling in ink; pricking in the margins. The manuscript also contains shorter texts with a different layout.

handDesc.p: The main text on is written by at least four different hands.

p.note: Margins filled with additions by the scribe or a contemporary hand.

Additions in the margins throughout by several different hands. The main layer consists of short one or two letter markings of theological authorities, made by the scribe or a contemporary hand. In several places text is written in a small script perpendicularly in the outer margin, e.g. : a chapter heading. Many of these additions have been partially lost due to trimming. There are also several other examples of different glosses or additions by other medieval hands, e.g. , , , ; and on in the bottom margin, a gloss in German: er nimpt ein sel di er gelt vnd wider geb Gvet vnd er daz er rechte nuetze vnder zer Gotes gnad uon der er rechte leb Sorig vnd geshephte des er getrivucher pleg di himelishen chrone die imer ob im sveb.

decoDesc.p: Main text in brown ink, rubrics in red, capitals occasionally touched in red.

decoNote.p: : opening plain initial over 3 lines in blue with flourishing in red. : plain initials over 2 lines alternating in red and blue. : dentelle initial over 4 lines in gold on a blue background, frame and counterspace in red. : foliate initial over 4 lines in blue on a gold background, frame in red.
